471,http://www.armslist.com/posts/4787471,For Sale:  RARE EARLY S/147 1938 WWII GERMAN K98 MAUSER RIFLE,"Florida, Florida, United States","$ 2,100","Listed On: Sunday, October 18, 2015",Rifles,Mauser                                                                                ,9mm Luger (9x19)                                                                                ,Double Action                                                                                ,Rifle,"This is a RARE original early WWII German K98 Mauser rifle made by the famous J.P. Sauer & Sohn company in Suhl, Germany in 1938. It has a 3-digit serial number in the ""a"" letter block which shows that it was one of the very first produced in 1938. It has original WWII German, ALL MATCHING SERIAL NUMBERS! It is in excellent condition with all original finish on both the metal and wood, and has scarce original markings for wartime overhaul by the German Spandau army depot in 1941!! The barrel & stock were both replaced at the depot, and numbered to match. The barrel was made by ""Geco"" and bears their classic logo. The Geco company is one of the biggest small arms / equipment companies in Germany and is still in business today. The barrel shank is correctly ""0.2"" marked indicating that is the 2nd barrel installed on this receiver. The stock was made by the original Mauser Oberndorf factory and bears their wartime code ""byf"" under the heel. The bolt take-down discs in the buttstock were made in-house at Spandau and are ""SUWW 1941 Su29"" marked. The stock is inpsection proofed ""Eagle over Su27"" under the grip and with a smaller ""Su29"" waffenamt on the side of the butt. The bayonet lug & buttplate were both armorers parts and are numbered to match the rifle in the same font. All these markings are textbook correct. This rifle was a US veteran's bringback war trophy and has NO IMPORT MARKINGS or other post-war markings! It has all original finish and has never been refinished! The stock has not been sanded, aggressively cleaned, or laquered and has lovely texture & color. The metal has all-original finish with a light pleasing patina and no rust or pitting. This is a very early German K98 made in 1938 when production numbers were lower and quality control was higher. The attention to detail on these early rifles is amazing with nearly every single part being serialized and waffenamt proofed, from the front sight blade to the action screws. Relatively few of these early rifles have survived in all-matching wartime configuration. The large majority of the earlier K98's went to the Russian front, and were eventually captured by the Russians who tore them apart, refinished, and reassembled them into completely mixed-up rifles. The small percentage that did make it back to the US were often sporterized and modified into custom hunting rifles in the first few decades after the war. These early K98's were extremely popular for this because of their high quality and solid construction. Finding one like this that escaped intact and original is rare indeed!! The bore is excellent and shiny with strong lands, deep grooves, and a tight muzzle. The pictures tell it all...for more pix and probably shipping details contact me here REDACTED"

855,http://www.armslist.com/posts/4787855,"For Sale:  1958 Winchester Pre-64 Model 70, 300 H&H Magnum","gerogia, Georgia, United States","$ 1,800","Listed On: Sunday, October 18, 2015",Rifles,Winchester                                                                                ,300 H&H Magnum                                                                                ,Bolt Action                                                                                ,Rifle,"Up for sale is one incredible, all-original, very rare Winchester Pre-64 Model 70 built in late 1958 and chambered for the venerable, accurate, and powerful 300 Holland & Holland (H&H)Magnum. This collector-grade rifle has never been afield and only fired 9 total rounds!!! I bought it in 2007 from the original owner, an older gentlemen from Salida, CO, who purchased the gun locally in late 1958 to hunt elk. Although a longtime 270 fan, he told me he succumbed to the ""Magnum Craze"" that was sweeping the country in the late 50s and early 60s, mounted a vintage Weaver 4X scope on the rifle, sighted it in with 9 rounds, and then put it in the bedroom closet and never hunted with or shot it again. According to the original owner, ""Jesus, the thing just kicked too damned much!"" and he reverted to using his beloved 270. I bought the rifle from him in 2007 to add to my Model 70 collection and, other than to receive a regular cleaning and inspection, I've never taken it out of the safe, shot it, or hunted with it. I'm only selling it because I have several Models 70 in 300 H&H and need the money for another project. So, up got grabs is a minty, all-original Pre-64 Model 70 in the desirable 300 H&H that, in 57 years, has only had nine bullets down the tube and never been afield. Metal is absolutely beautiful, 99%, with the only blemishes being one small rub on the extractor, one on the bolt knob, a minute scratch on the trigger guard, and only the slightest edge wear around the muzzle--all are depicted in the pics below. Rifling, as you might suspect, is sharp and crisp. Original sights, front sight hood,and sling swivels are intact and in wonderful condition. Bolt is serialized to the action. The original stock is uncut and wears the hard plastic butt plate appropriate for a 1958-vintage Model 70. Wood has some beautiful tiger stripe, as you can see in the pictures, and a few closet and safe marks, but no cracks or major imperfections. There's a elongated shallow dent on the right side of the butt; some tiny scratches near the butt plate, a shallow rub on the top of the comb; some slight scratches on both sides near the floor plate; and a tiny dent near the end of the forearm, all of which I've tried to show in the pictures. Checkering is sharp and well defined. Overall, I'd rate the stock at 97%. The period-correct Weaver scope and mounts have been on the rifle since new and the lenses are clear and bright. This rifle, a true safe queen, isn't 100% perfect, but it's as close to perfect as you're going to find for a 57-year-old rifle. In fact, I've been hyper-critical in my attempt to describe every minor flaw, so don't let that scare you--this is one beautiful rifle! It would make a superb addition to a Model 70 collection or serve equally well afield. I've tried to describe the rifle to the best of my ability and have attached the best possible pictures. Please ask if you have any questions or would like more photos. Winning bidder will pay the actual cost to have the rifle shipped insured in a hard case. I am not a licensed FFL holder, but a private citizen so, before bidding, make sure your FFL holder will accept shipment from me. Full payment in the form of a money order and The rifle will be shipped within two business days of the payment and FFL receipt. I do not accept returns, so please ask any questions before bidding. This well-cared-for rifle comes from a pet-free, smoke-free home. By bidding, you certify you live in a locale where it's lawful to receive and own this rifle. Again, ask any questions. Pre-64 Models 70 like this one don't pop up everyday, so don't let this opportunity to own a rare Rifleman's Rifle in 300 H&H Magnum slip away. I bought this rifle for $1800 in 2007 and that's exactly where I'm starting this auction--the market will determine the final sales amount. Bid often and early to make this quality, collectible Model 70 yours. I wish you good luck, happy bidding, and straight shooting.

The barrel on this rifle measures 25 1/4"" from muzzle to action, but Winchester advertised them as 26"" on the 300 H&H. The barrel is regular Winchester Proof steel, not stainless steel, and the bluing is dark blue, not the mat finish you'd find on a stainless barrel, for example, like the ones that commonly were fitted to 264 Win Mag Westerner rifles."
